07718nam a22011175i 9783110291926DE-B159720221004111318.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||221004t20122012gw     fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)853237356  a97831102919267 a10.1515/97831102919262doi  a(DE-B1597)177649  a(OCoLC)826652890  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE 7aREL0280002bisacsh00aFrom Just War to Modern Peace Ethics /ced. by Heinz-Gerhard Justenhoven, William A. Barbieri, Jr. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter, c[2012] 4c©2012  a1 online resource (353 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aArbeiten zur Kirchengeschichte ,x1861-5996 ;v12000tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tFrom Just War to Modern Peace Ethics: An Introduction -- tCicero: Just War in Classical Antiquity -- tAugustine’s Theology of Peace and the Beginning of Christian Just War Theory -- tAugustine: Peace Ethics and Peace Policy -- tThomas Aquinas and Humanitarian Intervention -- tForerunners of Humanitarian Intervention? From Canon Law to Francisco de Vitoria -- tFrancisco de Vitoria: Just War as Defense of International Law -- tMartin Luther on Peace and War: A Systematic Approach -- tMorality and Just War According to Francisco Suárez -- tSuárez, Aquinas, and the Just War: Self Defense or Punishment? -- tHugo Grotius: Just War Thinking Between Theology and International Law -- tKant’s Cosmopolitanism: Resource for Shaping a “Just Peace” -- tKant and the Just War Tradition -- tThe Holy See as International Person and Sovereign and Participant in International Law -- tFrom an Ethics of War to an Ethics of Peacebuilding -- tThe Peace Ethics of Pope John Paul II -- tList of Authors -- tIndex of Names0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis book rewrites the history of Christian peace ethics. Christian reflection on reducing violence or overcoming war has roots in ancient Roman philosophy and eventually grew to influence modern international law. This historical overview begins with Cicero, the source of Christian authors like Augustine and Thomas Aquinas. It is highly debatable whether Augustine had a systematic interest in just war or whether his writings were used to develop a systematic just war teaching only by the later tradition. May Christians justifiably use force to overcome disorder and achieve peace? The book traces the classical debate from Thomas Aquinas to early modern-age thinkers like Vitoria, Suarez, Martin Luther, Hugo Grotius and Immanuel Kant. It highlights the diversity of the approaches of theologians, philosophers and lawyers. Modern cosmopolitianism and international law-thinking, it shows, are rooted in the Spanish Scholastics, where Grotius and Kant each found the inspiration to inaugurate a modern peace ethic. In the 20th century the tradition has taken aim not only at reducing violence and overcoming war but at developing a constructive ethic of peace building, as is reflected in Pope John Paul II’s teaching.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 04. Okt 2022) 0aPeacexReligious aspectsxChristianity. 4aFriedensethik. 4aFriedenskonsolidierung. 4aGerechter Krieg. 4aInternationales Recht. 4aMoraltheologie. 7aRELIGION / Ethics.2bisacsh  aInternational Law.  aJust War Tradition.  aMoral Theology.  aPeace Building.  aPeace Ethics.1 aAraujo, Robert, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBarbieri, Jr., William A., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBeestermöller, Gerhard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrachtendorf, Johannes, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJustenhoven, Heinz-Gerhard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.